name: Demetris
text:
1/2022:  RECOMMEND, but 3.5 stars if possible due to 2 details:

If possible, go during the WEEKDAY for Unlimited bowl until 5pm for $11.99. I've hurt my arms & shoulders from bowling way too many games during this inexpensive time and improved my bowling scores.  (Thank you Round 1).

I've enjoyed going to Round 1 to relax and enjoy the oversized Pac-man game and bowl some stress away.  I have not tried the food nor drinks there because I just go in to play games.

Mostly clean, spacious and social distancing  protocols are  in effect.  Team members were constantly cleaning.  My only negative comment is that no one has cleaned the escalator entrance and it looks unwelcoming/unsightly.

Overall, give Round 1 a try and see what you think about it.  Enjoy the games!

name: Jordon Chavez
text:
Came upon this place walking around Coronado Center as I hadn’t been there in a couple of years. What a surprise!

I love arcades, and this one blew my mind. A lot of the games are the Japanese versions which is amazing to find, especially in The Land of Enchantment.

I love claw machines(the more challenging the better), and this place has TONS of them.

I purchased a $40 card and after a few arcade tries I went to try a claw.

After about 10 tries my card ran out of money, and I went to go re-load it. While I was gone, the progress that I had made on the item in the machine was re-set by a worker, which led me to a mini-freakout.

Luckily, he saw me and apologized, opened the machine and placed the item back where it was and let me continue. After about six more tries, I won! The key with the Japanese claw machines is PATIENCE.

I hd a wonderful time at this place, and will definitely be back.

My partner and I stopped here on our way home from Tulsa. It's cute inside and the staff we saw was cordial and attentive.

The salsa is mild and not very flavorful. It tastes mostly like tomatoes, but not terrible. We ordered regular queso. It was okay. Your standard runny white queso that's bland.

My partner and I split their story fajita plate to which I don't recall the name. It has chicken, steak, carnitas, shrimp and chorizo. The presentation was beautiful and the flavor was good. Nicely seasoned and all the meats were juicy and tender. There was a good ratio of meat to veggies. Overall, it was delicious and I'd choose this item again.

title: Hotel Bel-Air
description:
Set on a 12-acre estate with a lake and a lush garden, this refined luxury hotel is 5 miles from both I-405 and the exhibitions and gardens at the Getty Center.
 Posh rooms with limestone floors and wood ceilings feature free high-speed Wi-Fi and HDTVs, plus marble bathrooms with whirlpool tubs. Some provide fireplaces and/or patios with jetted pools. Suites come with living areas. A room with a balcony is available.
 A luxury car shuttle is complimentary. There’s an outdoor heated pool and a spa. An upscale restaurant serves American–Mediterranean fusion dishes and breakfast. A sophisticated bar has a grand piano and a photo exhibit.

description:
Set on a 12-acre estate with a lake and a lush garden, this refined luxury hotel is 5 miles from both I-405 and the exhibitions and gardens at the Getty Center.
 Posh rooms with limestone floors and wood ceilings feature free high-speed Wi-Fi and HDTVs, plus marble bathrooms with whirlpool tubs. Some provide fireplaces and/or patios with jetted pools. Suites come with living areas. A room with a balcony is available.
 A luxury car shuttle is complimentary. There’s an outdoor heated pool and a spa. An upscale restaurant serves American–Mediterranean fusion dishes and breakfast. A sophisticated bar has a grand piano and a photo exhibit.
label: real

name: Robbie33993
text:

The staff were all attentive and friendly
The prices were reasonable and we had a great time ... loved it... will def visit again when we're in town in October

title: Hilton Daytona Beach Oceanfront Resort
description:
This modern beachside hotel is a minute's walk from the Ocean Center convention facility and a 2-minute walk from the Daytona Lagoon waterpark.
 Airy, contemporary rooms offer custom-designed beds, TVs and Wi-Fi (fee); some have ocean views. Suites add separate living areas, and breezy beachfront cabanas include patios.
 Dining options include 7 restaurants and bars, including an oceanfront grill, a steakhouse and a relaxed beachfront bar. Other amenities include a spa and 2 outdoor pools, plus hot tubs and a fitness center. There's also a business center and over 60,000 sq ft of meeting space. A daily resort fee applies.

text:
This is one of my favorite places in New Haven. I’m an NYC expat always searching for places that remind me of my homeland. The food here is homemade, tasty and authentic. I’ve seen the reviews where people complain about the service,  and how only 1 person waits all the tables. Totally understandable if you’re in a major rush. It seems that the restaurant is family owned and operated which, to me, is a big plus. If you’re looking for fast food, this is the wrong place. If you’re looking for great food, home style vibes, great culture and a meal that will nourish your soul, come here.
By the way, don’t embarrass yourself by asking for a fork. Live a little and use your hands.

text: I love staying at the Honeycomb Bed & Breakfast whenever I visit Riding Mountain National Park.  The building is beautiful and so well kept, the rooms are great and the breakfast is perfect!  This trip they went above and beyond to help me when I had car problems.  Between Cindy and Anne, they picked me up, they drove me places (even out to look for critters) and they took me back to the car to meet up with the tow truck driver so I could head for home.
title: Honeycomb Bed & Breakfast
label: real

name: James Deng
text:
I ran into Honeycomb B&B by randomly search the Internet. Never heard about or used it before but it seemed it had got nice reviews and ratings on several travel websites. The price was also very good, especially compared to those resorts and cabins inside RMNP (Riding Mountain National Park). These are attractive enough so I decided to give it a try.

I have to tell you that I was not disappointed at all even though I  set my expectation very high. This B&B is right out of the town of Onanole, on a small hill right beside Hwy 10. Only 7km from the entrance of RMNP, you have easy and quick access to the park while still enjoy the quiet and beautiful setting of the B&B. The historic building has been beautifully restored and tastefully decorated. The room feels cozy and the bed is comfortable and supportive. The full breakfast (with bacon, egg/omelette, toasts, fruits, and coffee) was delicious. There are lots of other amenities for the gusts to enjoy, like the huge deck, the lounge room with TV, etc. Too bad I stayed for two nights only and was too busy to fully enjoy them. Will definitely come again, with my family.
title: Honeycomb Bed & Breakfast
label: real

name: Earl Kellner
text:
I was very surprised at the Honeycomb. I was a bit trepidatious as I had never stayed at a B&B before, but I was happily rewarded. You can tell a lot of hard work and love have gone into creating this place, and the hard work continues.

We enjoyed the back deck immensely and found ourselves out there every night. While we were there the owners, Cindy and Earl began another project on the grounds, preparing an area for wedding ceremonies to be held. I am certain that is going to be a great addition to the property and well received in the area.

The breakfast service was excellent. As someone that loves to cook, I could easily see the passion that went into the morning meal.

The beds are amazingly comfortable and the sheets are out of this world comfortable. The great news is that you can buy the same sheets and bring home a brand new set for yourself.

Looking forwadrs to a Wasagaming getaway next year and we know where we will want to book first.
title: Honeycomb Bed & Breakfast

The only thing that bothered me was that most of the games didn't have designated lines to wait in; people would just stand around it, so you kinda had to know whose turn was next.  And of course this means that some people cut their turn because they're not paying attention to everyone else who is there.
title: Electric Playhouse
label: real

name: Amanda Reyna
text: This place is pretty big. There is a lot of room to run and play. The reason I gave 4 stars is because there is not a lot of games but the games that are there have a lot of space to work in. My hope is that the more people go the quicker they can grow. Prices are reasonable for different age groups, I feel. I was not excited that they were out of some food and drinks that we wanted but I guess that is a nation wide issue.
title: Electric Playhouse

name: Monica Jaramillo
text: First time here and have to say now in my top 5 places to play at in Albuquerque!! What a blast! The games are all interactive and change to different ones as the time passes so always something new to check out! Bring your sneakers you will be doing lots of jumping, running and dodging♡ great for any age!

name: David Cox
text: Just had my daughter's 9th birthday at Electric Playhouse and it was a hit! The kids loved the party room and all the games, while the adults loved being able to play while enjoying some beverages. I would highly recommend it to anyone that has a birthday coming up for their young ones.

label: real

name: Jovelle C (Charmande)
text:
Firstly, they offer a 10% military discount ask for it at the door. It is a digital Meow Wolf style experience with food, bar and live DJ. The space provides an interactive digital entertainment for the whole family, first date, or friends. It can be very fun but I could imagine with a lot of people it could make for a busy experience with lines or frustration attempting to use an exhibit.
Most exhibits are like playing a VR game such as Beat Saber or a VR style Atari Pong while others are interactive or viewable digital art that continuously changes. A very unique experience. I did not try the food or drinks so I cannot speak to their quality or pricing but the main attraction here is the digital environment. Would definitely check out if in the Albuquerque area.

name: Melissa Jacobsen
text: First time here and we loved it! The staff is extremely friendly and helpful and guide you through initially to explain all the games. Once inside, there is a space that you can take selfies and they email you the pictures! The activities are never ending...just when we thought we had visited each game/activity, we walked back around and found new games.  They also provide complimentary iced water which was much needed after running around bopping aliens with balls. The Electric Playhouse can best be described as a baby version of Meow Wolf but it's closer and leaves you feeling less nauseous. It is pricey so this is definitely a once in awhile activity but worth the almost 2 hours of fun games and exercise!!

name: Holy Cow Music
text: This place is super unique. Not only is it a revolving conveyor belt sushi spot (which reminds me of Japan), but it has made to order foods on a self-service kiosk! You also insert your plate in a slot to keep track of your bill and total. You win a little toy prize if you get 15 (probably not worth it, but it's fun!) My only gripe is that this place does not serve very fresh ingredients... the fish quality is mediocre, and I DON'T recommend the Uni on ANY of the rolls. Please don't get it because I had it multiple times, and it definitely should not taste super bitter and rancid. I would not eat here more than once a month. But it is cheap though! $2.75 a plate I believe (for the most part). The Takoyaki octopus balls were amazing. The Taiyaki desert was also amazing.

name: Sharon Cho
text:
Returned during COVID-19 and had a pleasant experience. Conveyor service is stopped — definitely the right move for everyone’s safety. All plates are made to order, and honestly i think the quality is fresher (you can already tell i loved ordering fresh— see below). The prep time can be longer than just grabbing from the conveyor belt, but for the safety and the freshness, i can take it!!
Menu-wise, i prefer all the belly (toro?) sushi to regular sushi. Their tamago is COLD - didn’t expect that... you should ask for wasabi and soysauce. Udon was decently good - i think better value than miso soup. Oh, i like mackerel as well, but it might be too fishy(?) for some people.
———

Fresh sushi if you order fresh :)

name: Shant'e T
text: I really enjoyed this hotel and glad I selected it for my first trip to LA. It's directly across the street from the train station and surrounded by several bus lines. There's also a really nice church next to it that's worth checking out. I believe it's the Oasis church. The hotel staff were helpful and friendly. The rooms were clean, quiet and the beds comfortable. My first time seeing the Hollywood sign was from my room! Exciting! Commissary, the hotel restaurant was pretty decent. It's aesthetically pleasing giving it an overall good vibe. I even received cilantro seeds in a package along with my bill which was a nice touch. One issue was the kitchen eating area setup. Because the kitchen is in the hotel and the eating area is separated, the staff had to walk outside with my food resulting in pieces from trees on my plate. Also, while there, a pool party was given. During this time I attempted to get a non-alcoholic drink and was told to go outside with the party goers to order a drink or go to another restaurant downstairs in the hotel lobby. I was aware of the pool party in advance and planned to relax by the poolside once it was over. I was unable to do this since the party ended later than the time announced. Besides these few annoyances, I would certainly return to the Line and reccomend it to others.
title: The LINE LA
description:
Adjacent to the Wilshire / Normandie subway station, this hip hotel in a midcentury building in Koreatown is 4 miles from the Los Angeles County Museum of Art.
 Industrial-chic rooms with concrete-patterned wallpaper, funky original art and floor-to-ceiling windows feature free Wi-Fi, work desks and chairs upholstered with vintage Mexican fabric. Some have views of the Hollywood Hills, and suites add separate living rooms and dressing areas.
 Amenities include an exercise room, loaner bikes and an outdoor pool with daybeds and a greenhouse lounge. There’s also a cafe, a buzzy restaurant and a lobby bar.

name: Paul LeMarc Brown
text:
This is my Mecca. My west coast home away from my east coast home. Impeccably-designed rooms framing vistas of K-Town rooftops and the Hollywood Hills. Gilded decor, interesting ceramic pottery, and industrial concrete walls (did you find the 3D wallpaper?) spark my joy.

Now let’s chat about the grub. In a rush, no problem, grab a matcha latte and panini from the lobby cafe. Feeling lonely, because you were catfished last week, grab brunch upstairs in your finest unisex blouse. Carbs are your bestie, so tell the french toast your naughtiest thoughts. There’s even a run club, just TRY it or better yet get a mimosa to-go and skip behind the group in your finest spandex.

name: David singleton
text:
Nice hotel. Enjoyed our stay. Good if you want to be in k-town. Although as it pitched itself as this new cool trendy hotel its lacking a few things:
1. the latest style of watching TV. No on demand or netflix etc. The connections to attach you device didn't work and didn't have the ability to connect latest Android devices.
2. Noise insulation from outside and noise between rooms. We were women in the middle of the night by noisy neighbours 2 nights. And the Windows are really thin and let on noise and drafts.
3. Service although friendly in general wasn't up to the standard of say a hotel like The Ace.

What was good was:
The room was comfortable.
The view from the room was great of the Hollywood hills.
Cool room design
The reception staff were good

name: Alicia Mold
text:
This hotel exceeded my expectations. The staff are all SUPER FRIENDLY and helpful. The atmosphere is divine. The decor is refreshing and unique. Doesn’t feel like just any of hotel. Beds are super comfy (I have a bad back.) The way the rooms are laid out, makes such good use of the space. The only thing, and I mean the ONLY THING, I could comment on was the water pressure is a bit soft. But that’s it.

The pool area is stunning, a nice place to relax and read a book while tanning and having a drink/snack. Good wifi. Haven’t dined in the greenhouse lounge yet but will do so today. I have one more night here and I am happy we chose this spot! Korea town feels safe at night and has tons of good late night eateries!

Will definitely be staying here in my future trips back to LA. 10/10.

name: Dean Krapf
text:
A whole lot to say about our visit.

It was opening day so things were bound to go a bit sideways.

Pros:

Kammi our ref - absolutely amazing! She was attentive to the group, very friendly but had no problem calling out safety items the instant someone's mask wasn't all the way down or an uncovered barrell. She was great and I highly recommend you request her if you are taking a group.

The different games fields were fun and challenging. Our group had seasoned vets and first time adults and teens so it was well balanced. Kammi started us out easy and then introduced respawns and play until you're out of paint which everyone loved.

The field paint quality was really good in my opinion. Very consistent and I wish I had a marker that could really sling it.

The whole staff was friendly and went above and beyond to ensure everyone was safe and having fun.

Cons:

The hiccups of opening day with any business, but the owner and his team took it in stride and powered through.

Ran out of air so they were transporting tanks back and forth. Also ran out of cases of paint but that too was resolved with a trip the their warehouse.  These two items didn't affect our play or the amount of fun we had.

The rental markers were all over the place. Different models, broken detents, etc.  Once again - opening day, but it's on the calendar - clean and check everything weeks in advance. We replaced a few tank o-rings ourselves from our parts kits to save time.

No chronographing of walk on players. The rentals were slow and hot and some walk on teens were definitely pushing 300 fps. That's a safety thing especially with rental masks/lenses and horrible experience for young teens playing for the first time.

I am very glad our group made it down and even with said hiccups we had a blast and will be back in the future.

name: Randy M
text:
Here’s the good and the bad and the very bad.

The good: The front desk staff who checked us in was very nice, the front office is very nice, and the shower was very nice. Get the picture?

The bad: this is an old motel that needs updating. The carpets are ripped, the sofa is ripped and covered up with a coverlet rather than replacing it, there is a mirror in front of the sofa rather than a TV to look at, and the bed is old and sagging in the middle. And this is an executive suite!Figure that out. Just look at the pictures.

The very bad: we booked a King executive suite. We were told that someone had already taken that suite and extended their stay. Instead of telling them that we had a reservation and that the motel could move them to another room, we were told that we would be moved to another room. We were given a queen executive suite. No discount. No offer of points. Just a “sorry, we can’t guarantee a room.”  When we complained, the manager was quite generous (please note that is sarcasm) by giving  us a whole 500 points. Wow-wee!

The very very bad: And they have the nerve to charge over $200 for the room.

PS The microwave was unplugged and that was because it didn’t work, which I reported to the morning clerk. They don’t serve breakfast in the motel. You have to go next door to the restaurant and the tip is not included. But honestly, we wished we had skipped breakfast because the cook must’ve had a bad morning and most of the food was not cooked enough - runny eggs although ordered fried hard, hash browns hard on one side/soft on the other, the same with the English muffin.

Recommendation? Try another hotel/motel in the area if you can.
title: Best Western Colorado River Inn
description:
Located just off Historic Route 66, this laid-back hotel is a mile from both Rivers Edge Golf Course and Needles Marina Park.
 Offering free Wi-Fi and flat-screen TVs, the simple rooms have coffeemakers, microwaves and minifridges. Suites add sitting areas with pull-out sofas.
 Freebies include hot breakfast served in a cafe adjacent to the hotel, plus parking. There's also an outdoor pool, a hot tub and a sauna.
label: real

name: Vikki Horchar
text: Employees are nice. Working  4am to 2pm. Came back to the room at 1:30pm on a Thursday & our room still wasn't clean. No worries,  it's not like I'm a slob. Went to the housekeeping cart & called out into a room I assumed was being cleaned & nobody answered or was in the room. I put my dirty towels in the bag hanging off the cart & grabbed clean ones & was good to go. No worries.  Put a do not disturb on my door & all was well. My complaint is that there were so many flies in my room when I arrived on the day before. I used a hand towel & killed them all. The a/c filters were filled with lint, like a clothes dryer filter. (The pictures I'm showing here are AFTER I cleaned them). I pulled them out & banged them together outside my door & the lint flew off into the wind. Then I rinsed them off in the shower & dried them & put them back. No worries 👍 sneezing problem solved. Also had to use a hand towl in room 114 to slam in the bottom of the entry door where critters could crawl in from outside.  The insulation on the bottom right corner of the door was missing.  Showerhead had bad water pressure due to corrosion as well & several outlets in the room didn't work. Other than that the place isn't that bad. I'll return for work but bring a flyswatter & clean the a/c filters in the room with each visit.

name: Arianna Kent
text:
An absolutely wonderful stay at this clean motel.

I am paranoid about travelling due to the current pandemic, but I didn’t have a worry in the world with how spotless and clean this room was. Felt comfortable, and like home. No dirt, dust bunnies ANYWHERE.

Check in was fast an efficient. This motel could be charging way more than they are for the quality of rooms they provide.

The rooms had pots, pans, dishes, utensils, and whatever else you could need to make yourself a quick meal if you didn’t feel like going out to a nearby restaurant.

The bed was comfy, which is a rare find in most motels. They also has 3 different mattress protectors on the mattress itself, all extremely clean. They provide an additional blanket on top of the shelf as well.

I was also extremely grateful for the working air conditioner, another rare find in motels.

If you are making a cross country drive like I was, I highly recommend planning to stop here for a good nights rest.

(Also I greatly appreciated the little cat feet socks on the chair legs, just adorable.)

name: David Thomas-Jensen
text: I have known the proprietor, Mohammed, since he was the head chef at Big Marina on 49th and Central Northeast. He's a good kind and generous father, excellent chef, and you people Uptown are extremely lucky to have this place here end capping eat Street. This place is known for its Mediterranean fare, hummus, baba ganoush, tabouli, Gyros, sambusas, grilled chicken, roast chicken, Kafka, pot roast, BBQ rib tips, arguably some of the best mashed potatoes, three kinds of seasoned rice, countless other dishes. You need to bring an appetite, and expect to overeat if you plan on going with the all-you-can-eat buffet option. A more practical and dietary way, is to make your selections ala carte to go, even if you just sit down and eat. That way you take a measured amount, it controls the overeating, and it's more frugal. Mohammed doesn't mind either way, DIY card method means you're less likely to waste food, and as a Muslim, wasting food is considered a sign of disrespect for the gift of the meal, from Allah. I usually get a decent size lunch, for less than $10, ala carte. But enough with words let your eyes be the judge.

name: Tom Bandini
text:
We came to Hilton Head Island for Memorial Day because we never get away for the holidays. It was such a pleasurable experience. The resort was not very busy for being a holiday weekend. There was lots of activities and there is immediate beach access.

The rooms were a little humid even with the air conditioning at 65 which made for some sticky night sleeps but still very cold for the hot weather we experienced.

The food at View 32 was excellent. We highly recommend the Grilled Cheese BLT Panini! I wish they still had the lobster roll from a few years ago when we visited but I was able to find that at a nearby local restaurant. The servers we had were also amazing!

I also had delightful experiences with Clive from the Front Desk and Madison from Guest Services. They had exceptional customer service skills which is the reason I choose Marriott!

We will definitely be visiting again! Thank you to the Westin staff for your hospitality!

name: Gavin Fulmer
text:
The hotel is not cleaning rooms. They claim that it's to address covid that they aren't doing any room cleaning during stays. But our room was still dirty even when we first checked in! So, they just aren't cleaning enough in between, either. The tub was downright grimy, there was sand everywhere, and the place doesn't smell fresh. Had very mixed service experience, some front desk staff are trying hard but some on the phone line are actually rude.

The location is great with two paths to a wonderful beach, both paths have freshwater spray to get sand off. There are also multiple pools with options that please all the family -- including a shaded pool if you want to enjoy a swim even after a sunburn. So if the service were better this would be a great stay.

name: Mrs. Red Beard
text:
We were able to book this fun hotel during an “off week”. We spent 2/5 days without leaving. They truly offer everything.

Not long after we checked in, they sent us 2 free app coupons & a bottle of champagne with a thoughtful note for our anniversary.

Our king room was clean & spacious. The bed was SO fluffy, which I loved. We had a partial ocean view which was nice bc that wasn’t what I booked. Most reviews say rooms are outdated, I guess they kind of are but it’s not terrible. Every day we walked past rooms being cleaned, like furniture flipped over & scrubbing. (I’m sure it’s easier for them to do in down time.) I was seriously impressed. The room had complementary water & coffee, a fridge, iron, hair dryer..etc Our only inconvenience was no microwave for leftovers.

All of the staff was so welcoming and kind! Someone said they were short handed, like everywhere, but we didn’t really notice until our last day when a lot more people started coming in. Even then, it wasn’t a problem for us.

The Spa! I wish we would’ve thought to book services sooner. It’s pricey but worth it!

The pools are nice & grounds well manicured. Pools close at 9 which was disappointing. We wanted to use the hot tub at night but couldn’t seem to get there before then.

The walk to the beach is easy with a nice path. We took advantage of the lifeguards umbrella & chair rentals. I believe it was $40 a day. The beach was a little crowded the 2 days we were able to go. I just thought, I couldn’t imagine how busy it would be in the summer.

Last, find the breakfast buffet! They have everything. It was wild. Lol

Overall, we would stay here again if it was in our budget & low crowds. This place is expensive along with every extra thing to go with it. It was our anniversary so we splurged. We enjoyed every day!!!

name: Jessica Woods
text: I was looking forward to eating my salad but unfortunately I didn't realize the dressing was expired until after I poured it. The packaging was very sticky & the dressing had a yellow hue to it. I called the store immediately to request a refund or a new salad to be delivered. They didn't have a driver tonight. So I requested the refund. The employee didn't believe me because he said they opened a new box & it is not expired. I told him the package is sticky & the expiration is July 19 ,2021. So posting the review to show that mistakes can be made and everyone is not scamming for money. I would rather eat my salad than recieve a refund. Please check the packaging not just the manufacturer box mistakes can be made. I've just realized the croutons was expired too. Check the inventory.

title: Wooden Spoke Restaurant
label: real

name: Leah Michelle
text:
We are here last night, December 17th 2021, for my my husband's 28th birthday.

We have lived in Baldwin for 2 years and those years have been pretty rough, we were so lucky to find an apartment in sweet and quiet Baldwin City. We love it here and plan on buying a home. We've experienced quite a few events here but this was our first local restaurant. We were finally able to come to The Wooden Spoke after hearing so much about it and we brought friends from out of town.

What a charming, down-home, relaxed place. The parking lot felt like you were pulling into a old-time drive in, but you get out of your car and reach the door and it feels like you are standing outside of someone's well-loved home. The tables reminded me of my own kitchen tables in my childhood home. I felt comfortable as soon as I sat down. The waitress was extremely attentive, her energy was calm and sincere. Our drink orders were taken immediately, our appetizers came out quickly and the entrees were the best home cooking we all have had in many years.

We ordered the KC strip, the ribeye, the bourban steak and the spoke burger, spoke fries, mash potatoes, the chilli, mozzarella sticks, potato skins, and the wings in this beautiful honey brown sauce that was sweet, spicy, smoky and honestly it was incredible. I love WINGS and these took the trophy from me and my friends!

Our food and plates were hot, the food was fast. All the steaks were cooked as asked, all steaks were medium rare, juicy, delicious and quite big. Burger was done just well and had a classic burger taste.

The alcoholic beverages were delicious and made strong.

My daughter ordered the kids chicken strips and she said they were very good, we loved the fries. The spoke burger was amazing and the mustard tasted homemade. My husband especially loved the chilli. Overall, the food was spectacular. The service was fast and friendly, the environment was clean and comfy. We will definitely be back.

Thank you wooden spoke staff and mad respect and kudos to the Chef who made an unforgettable night full of nostalgic decor, warm and friendly interaction and phenomenal home-cooking! See you again soon!!

I wish I could add more photos but it was such a good time, I didn't think about taking a bunch, I just soaked in the night! ⚪️

name: Nikki Westerfield
text:
I am disgusted. As I just sit in this bed because I don’t want me feet all over who knows how many guests before me. We stopped here so we didn’t have to continue to drive on our long trip. All we wanted was a clean hotel where we could sleep and shower with our two children! The shower even has black hairs! Black hairs were all over the first room and we asked to switch to find the same thing. The floors are not vacuumed at all. It’s unreal. I have never stayed at a Wyndham hotel but it looked VERY nice in the photos and I never imagined it would be this dirty. The cleaning in this hotel... well there obviously wasn’t any real cleaning done. There should never be leftovers from other strangers in a hotel I paid for. I would have rather drove three more hours then not have a nice place to sleep and shower at. I am very upset and I have NEVER in my life wrote a review. I am not hard to please! The Wi-Fi code does not work. The phone does not work. The phone plug keeps falling out every time I pick up the phone. The top layer of the sheet had dirt on it or food. Looks like cake. I stay at many hotel. This is unacceptable. Also On top of this. I was told you guys price match. There was a deal online that was $20 cheaper than the right here and they said they could not do it. So even more annoyed right now that I came here because I thought I was getting a deal. After having heart issues with my bank it took a little longer than necessary which is totally my fault. My car got blocked because were out of town. I would have paid the extra money to stay in a clean hotel but after carrying all of her bags and everything up for four people, me and my husband have to work tomorrow. And both of our kids are ready for bed. None of us will be showering in the bathroom and we are all disgusted to the point we don’t want to get off our beds u less we have our shoes on.
Livid to say the least. The cleaning lady left a envelope for a tip???? She has to be joking. She needs to be fired. Oh!!! and the what class that my daughter went to use had a big black hair in it. Look close at pics! Gross!!!!

Staff is very friendly. I will say. They were nice. Although a guy followed us up to make sure the second room was clean. It wasn’t.. and he walked away and did nothing. I am convinced all rooms are this dirty or I would ask for another!

name: Jacqueline Hartman
text:
We stopped at a quick one night stop to get some sleep, shower, and back get on the road. It was on the way to where we were headed, so it worked perfectly. Things that need improvement: 1. The thermostat. It was not accurate and as you can see my thermostat said it was 65% humidity, because theirs wasn’t working and wouldn’t trigger air on its own. My husband continued to smell mildew every time he walked into the room, I must have missed it the 2 times I walked in. 2. The vent, it could use some cleaning. I am not sure how clean the air we manually forced out of it was.
Good things on why I scored it high: 1. Price was great. 2. Location for us was awesome. 3. It did the job provide a nice firm mattress for us to get some good shut eye. The pillows could have been comfier, but for the price I will not complain! 4. The one person we interacted with at the desk was great. 5. Had a pool, we didn’t use it but I heard kids were enjoying it when I was checking in. 6. Overall thought things were relatively clean! 7. The bathroom was super cute and had a cool mirror/light. 8. There was a tv, but we didn’t use it. It was small for some standards, but I didn’t care as we were actually just using it for sleep.

If you are looking for a quick stop to get some good sleep and this is on the way, would 100% recommend. If you are looking for a fancier vacation hotel I would probably look elsewhere, but I’m not sure if that’s the area for fancier hotels.

name: ML Walton
text:
We arrived late at night, so we didn't inspect the room very well before crawling in bed and falling asleep. When we woke up, I could see oily fingerprints on the headboard, something sneezed or splashed onto the TV, someone's grocery store card they accidentally left behind, and some rather dirty looking blood stains on one of the pillow cases.

The tiles and grout near the tub were a bit in disrepair, but overall things appeared tolerably clean and satisfactory unless you looked closely. I feel like the cleaning job is one of the biggest customer services a hotel can offer, because you don't want to feel like you're constantly touching other people's left behind germs, lube residue, etc. It was a major detraction.

The breakfast was okay but the lady behind the counter (responsible for cooking the eggs and everything) seemed spread very thin in her duties.

I would have preferred paying a little more at this hotel for it to be a place with a better cleaning service. If it wasn't for the room  cleanliness the experience would have been more like 3½ stars for me.

name: Daniel Gallemore
text: Called at 3:51pm to ask if pool and hot tub were working, was told that they were. Drove there arriving about an hour later, booked room, went to room and changed clothes. We go down to the pool and nephew starts swimming in the pool (there's a women and child there as well.) There's a sign around hot tub saying it's closed so we go ask what the deal is since that was a deciding factor of where we stayed since the nephew was with us. The guy gets kinda rude and says the pool is closed too, but nobody seems to know why. He goes to the pool and puts makeshift sign on the door and tells everyone they need to leave. We go to room, change back into regular clothes, and head downstairs. Upon speaking to the manager apparently the pool is fine but hot tub has a leaking pipe (not what sign says) so it'll remain closed. I'm giving 2 stars rather than 1 because the refund process was pretty seamless. The place looks nice, but being told everything is good, driving almost an hour and checking in to realize it's not, then the lack of communication and poor attitude of the desk worker... ehhh. The manager was nice enough when we spoke at the end, but we were leaving at that point.

I came here for a goodbye party since I was moving to DC. Best of the Wurst is one of the best kept secrets of New Jersey. Tucked away with seating by the River so you can watch boats go by. The owner is extremely friendly and the food is damn good. I had the kielbasa sandwich and it was 10/10 the meat, the onions, and the MELTED CHEESE phenomenal!

On a side note it’s pretty cool to walk around and see the boats around the marina.
title: Best of the Wurst German Kitchen
label: real

name: amfr_831
text: Always a wonderful and authentic meal that you can count on. Joe and Chef Wilhelm always stop by to say hello and chat. BoTW never disappoints! A real hidden gem here in Riverside.

name: Jordan P
text:
The waitress was great, and some of the food seemed really interesting considering we didn't intend on coming here but the place we were meaning to go to was closed. The place in dingy, so be prepared for that; the sign is in disrepair, badly needs paint, the patio section desperately needs to be remodeled, broken down cars out front (as well as a broken down boat). Now, as to the food: pretty good. I got the Rancocas Burger and was generally pretty impressed other than it being overcooked (ordered medium, came out well. I still ate it cause I'm not that annoying about my food). While I could be way off base, it had a sort of lack of flavor that's reminiscent of cheapish frozen beef. Not trying to spread lies if maybe it was just a bit under seasoned but that's what it reminded me of.

All in all I'll give it another shot at some point, maybe on a busier day.

name: KL Dice
text:
We had mixed feelings about our stay at this Hilton.  First off, the pictures of the family suites are deceiving.   We thought their would be an extra room with a king or two doubles.  Their was not.  It's all one big room.  When you walk in their are bunk beds, (the ceiling was low and the ladder was steep) then a hallway, bathroom ( with no lock on it, by the way) then the bed with a table & sofa ( that turns into a bed) then balcony.   They do have multiple restaurants, but  all of them were pricey.  They did give us a free ice cream, it was pretty good.  Alex who checked us in was very helpful.

They have multiple pools, but if you dont get  out to the lounge chairs by seven your out of luck!  Beachfront was great!  You have to rent chairs & umbrellas for the beach, so we just brought our own.  The hot tub in the indoor pool jets did not work.

Overall we enjoyed our stay.
We ate a lot off property since we had a lot of activites planned.
We really enjoyed the beachfront access & the views.

Weather, Restaurants... including a Spectacular evening at Seagars Steakhouse 💥, Pools, Spa, Beach Umbrella/Chair Facilitators, and Beach Bar Waitresses simply complimented the perfect weather , clean White Beaches our entire stay. name: Jonathan Friedopfer
text:
Quick drive from Atlanta. Fun place with table games and slots which pay out well!

Update- returned and absolutely did not enjoy. After visiting many random casinos around the country and then returning I realized that the slots are outdated as well as very tight. I never expect to win however I do expect to be entertained and have fun. Additionally, all the tables had minimum $25 bets with some at $100 min. I'll happily bet $25-$100 when I'm feeling it however mandatory on every bet can drain your stack fairly quick.

The atmosphere is also dull. I enjoy the other location in cherokee a lot more.

Back to slots. Many make you hit max bet for chance to get progressive. 90% don't have any cool bonus features. The few which  have features like spin wheel or free games rarely hit. Even if a bonus feature only wins $1 at at least gives some excitement.  This place is supposed to be fun and exciting. Additionally, most times the slots are full so very few options to even pick from to play.
Why do random casinos like in Iowa, wendover- NV, FL, CT, etc  all have new fun exciting games with bonuses, freeplay, bonus side games, etc and not here. Why do all these other places allow to hit progressives on any bet? Why do they have better music, comps, atmosphere, etc?
I never disliked a casino before but do now. 🤦‍♂️🤷‍♂️
title: Harrah's Cherokee Valley River
description:
This basic casino resort is 4 miles from the Cherokee Historical Museum and 5 miles from the Cherokee County Courthouse, which dates from 1926.
 The streamlined rooms feature Wi-Fi (fee), flat-screen TVs and minifridges. Some offer sofabeds.
 The no-nonsense casino offers slots, table games and a bar. Dining options include 4 casual restaurants and a coffee shop.

title: Quality Inn & Suites
description:
This straightforward hotel is 4.7 miles from the Worlds of Fun amusement park and 7.2 miles from Kauffman Stadium, home of the Kansas City Royals.
 All rooms have en suite bathrooms, coffeemakers and free WiFi, as well as flat-screen TVs, minifridges and microwaves. Some rooms add minifridges, and wet bars or kitchenettes. Suites include pull-out sofas and/or living rooms.

name: Mrs. K. (Big Mama)
text:
For the price point (a little over $100) it was a very good experience. The mattress was perfect, 4 fluffy clean pillows, blankets and bedding were clean and smelled lovely.
The carpets were also clean and didn't feel gross when you walked on it barefoot. The bathroom was also clean but a star lost for the condition of the tub. It was very oddly shaped and slippery when I was taking a shower, BE CAREFUL!
The general smell of the hotel was clean and pleasant when you walked in, what a nice surprise! There is a decent FREE breakfast bar in the morning but come early to avoid the herds.
Check in was done professionally if not overly friendly. The hotel is located on a dead end but strangely, it's a very peaceful and quiet place. 4 ☆☆☆☆ We will def come back to stay when we're in KC.

They kept trying for cash instead of a card, seemed reluctant to refund the room cost, though it was returned as well as the unmentioned $100 deposit. Card was charged twice for $70. Lots of people hanging around outside. Didn't feel comfortable leaving my car unattended even just for the 5 minutes we were in the room. Pretty sure the 5* reviews are fake. DO NOT STAY HERE. Go to the Comfort Inn a couple of miles away.

name: Rebecca Larsen
text:
If I could give negative stars, I would.  The room itself was a little sketchy with something growing on the wall, the ceiling was pealing in the corner and was breaking away along the exterior wall. The tub had serious rust stains, and the phone didn't work. That's relevant because I needed to call the front desk when I woke up and found that my car had been broken into.

I had to call on my phone and the front desk just asked what room I was in. They didn't even apologize that this crime had been committed, didn't offer to send someone to clean up the glass, call the cops, anything. And when I checked out they didn't say anything. I received more sympathy from the cops (just filed a report, they didn't send anyone out) and the glass repair company Safelite. They apologized that this had happened and helped me find a repair location that can get me in tomorrow in a different state. Quality Inn isn't quality at all. They don't care about your stay at all.

name: Mrs. K. (Big Mama)
text:
For the price point (a little over $100) it was a very good experience. The mattress was perfect, 4 fluffy clean pillows, blankets and bedding were clean and smelled lovely.
The carpets were also clean and didn't feel gross when you walked on it barefoot. The bathroom was also clean but a star lost for the condition of the tub. It was very oddly shaped and slippery when I was taking a shower, BE CAREFUL!
The general smell of the hotel was clean and pleasant when you walked in, what a nice surprise! There is a decent FREE breakfast bar in the morning but come early to avoid the herds.
Check in was done professionally if not overly friendly. The hotel is located on a dead end but strangely, it's a very peaceful and quiet place. 4 ☆☆☆☆ We will def come back to stay when we're in KC.

title: Hilton Daytona Beach Oceanfront Resort
description:
This modern beachside hotel is a minute's walk from the Ocean Center convention facility and a 2-minute walk from the Daytona Lagoon waterpark.
 Airy, contemporary rooms offer custom-designed beds, TVs and Wi-Fi (fee); some have ocean views. Suites add separate living areas, and breezy beachfront cabanas include patios.
 Dining options include 7 restaurants and bars, including an oceanfront grill, a steakhouse and a relaxed beachfront bar. Other amenities include a spa and 2 outdoor pools, plus hot tubs and a fitness center. There's also a business center and over 60,000 sq ft of meeting space. A daily resort fee applies.
label: real

name: Michelle Maloy
text: This is one of the best hotels in Daytona by far. In fact the only two places that I will stay at the Hilton or at the Shores hotel. One of the things that makes the Hilton so nice is that they have recently renovated the property and it has a clean and beachy feel as old as you walk in. Ciara at the front desk if super awesome and friendly. One of the best things about the hotel is the location. It is located right next to the boardwalk so you can walk over and play video games and do a little budget shopping as well and go to the movie or go get ice cream. There are also several different vendors doors as well as a movie theater. Joe’s crabshack as well as bubblegum are both walking distance in addition to marble ice cream company. The hotel also have a Starbucks inside as well as a nice steakhouse called Hyde Park which is fancy and serves premium steaks,chops and cocktails. There is also another restaurant on site that serves breakfast lunch and dinner. It’s nice that once you park your car you don’t have to take it out until you’re ready to leave the hotel. The bellman staff here is also extremely friendly.

This modern beachside hotel is a minute's walk from the Ocean Center convention facility and a 2-minute walk from the Daytona Lagoon waterpark.
 Airy, contemporary rooms offer custom-designed beds, TVs and Wi-Fi (fee); some have ocean views. Suites add separate living areas, and breezy beachfront cabanas include patios.
 Dining options include 7 restaurants and bars, including an oceanfront grill, a steakhouse and a relaxed beachfront bar. Other amenities include a spa and 2 outdoor pools, plus hot tubs and a fitness center. There's also a business center and over 60,000 sq ft of meeting space. A daily resort fee applies.
label: real

name: Elizabeth Robertson
text:
PROS:  The location is PRIME!   It is right on the boardwalk and convenient to the amusement park next door and the pier.  The breakfast buffet is TO DIE FOR!

CONS:  (none of which merit giving this resort less than 5 stars).  The resort itself is quite dated, so don't expect fancy rooms, but -especially for a beachfront resort- the common areas are in good shape.  Expect to pay exorbitant prices for everything within the resort, as goes with any vacation resort.

TIPS:  I definitely recommend spending the money for valet parking because the self-parking is a good distance away and terribly inconvenient (and isn't that much cheaper).  Try and get a room on the upper floors, beachfront, because the view is great!

I would definitely stay here again!

When I had something to say about the extra fees the lady at the desk just threw up her hands and told her supervisor "You deal with him" and walked away leaving me at the counter by myself until the supervisor  could come over and help me 15 minutes later.

name: Mike Killian
text: I usually avoid these corporate giant hotel chains, but with COVID-19 they were one of the only ocean views still open in April, so my lady & I reserved a standard King Bed ocean view. Came to $125 with my FL Resident discount. They did waive the outrageous $25 per day resort fee since no amenities were available, but still charge the daily parking fee. These extra charges are why I avoid such places & stick to quiet low-key motels, but they are closed currently due to no travelers because of COVID-19. Fortunately no crowds at least. Hotel is dated, tho our room was clean. They should have the pool open since FL leaves that decision to the owner, there is no "shut down the pools" order by the state or county. With 4 or 5 guests in the whole hotel and being that chlorine kills viruses, it would have been nice to use the pool. When I reserved the room on the phone they tried to upsell me on "Vacation Ownership" too which I of course turned down, being that I already hated having to pay $100 in parking fees for a 2 day stay (2 vehicles)  They get 3 stars because the room was clean, view was good, no tourists to ruin the chill quiet I wanted & the front desk lady was nice.

name: John Stegman
text:
Came for the Tuesday deal. Was told it would be 20-30min wait for leagues and parties to end. However, league doesn’t end until 9pm and about 3/4 of the lanes are dedicated to league games. We ended up waiting over and hour to bowl. Our issue is they knew league wouldn’t end until 9 and they gave us a complete unrealistic waiting time. Also multiple lanes (many next to each other) were completely open but they wouldn’t allow anyone to bowl next to league games. This is incredibly frustrating for local patrons who want to take advantage of their weekly deals. So disappointing. Also if you plan to have a night with a lot of people at the bar it would be nice to have more then one bartender to serve drinks took forever to get anything

Came back with a Groupon, just a heads up if you use a Groupon you have restrictions on your lane that are not listed.

I love the Sunday morning 10am to Noon games because it's only $2 a game which is really nice, my roommate almost bowled a 300 last Sunday. The only issue I have is that the lanes are extremely dry if you go for a late night special, if you are throwing house balls it's fine but if you have your own professional balls then it can be frustrating.

I would still go back due to the food and staff. Even valet was cool. #supportblackbusiness❤️

name: Victor N
text:
This was a great experience! We did the Sporting KC room with 5 adults plus a 5-year old and loved it! No spoilers, so all I'll say is don't let the small room deceive you. Plenty of clever things to discover.

They will give as many hints as you would like. Only the first requested 3 hints are free though. Anything beyond those 3 result in a 3-minute penalty each. You still get a full hour to break out, no matter how many hints you use. You're time will just look longer than one hour. This is how people get scores of 64 minutes, even though you only have an hour max.

The do give free hints if they see that you're stuck. These do not count against your 3 free requested hints, nor do they penalize your time.

My advice for the uninitiated is to not be afraid to use the hints! Especially if you're not going to try again at a later date. Enjoy the puzzles, but don't let them frustrate you. Make sure someone is keeping track of time so that you can pace the free hints.

The parking was a bit confusing. The building is close to some apartments and there's a few signs that explicitly say "no parking" for break out KC. Parking directly in front of the entrance says "for tenants and patrons only", which we had no idea what that meant. We ended up parallel parking in the street, just to be safe.

name: Marcie Molina
text:
I loved the play and splash area!  I wish I had known about it sooner. There is a Denver Zoo App with a map to help ease but it lacks a logo to specify children interactive areas such as the sand play area, jump like an animal etc. They have a whole play area for children, toddlers and up. The new Dinosaur exhibits are awesome and we hope they're here to stay, or at least come back next summer!! They have a dig for bones activity and a dinosaur to climb on by the carousel. They also have a whole parakeet section where you can go in and feed the birds. I wish they had a place you could feed the giraffes.

Boo at the Zoo is always a hit, we love the chapstick (only Toyota was handing out the chapstick this year). The light at the Zoo has severely improved since the last time I attended in 2011. There are so many more lights and fun events etc.

FYI you cannot bring balloons into the zoo, but you can bring food, snacks, juice boxes, and water. Food isn’t too expensive nor disgusting if you have to buy here too. Beer and BBQ is sold at the Zoo if you need that as a selling point to get the hubby to go.

name: Andrew Parker
text:
My work involves a lot of travel and I’ve been fortunate to visit multiple arcades around the world, including Japan. I’d easily rank the four Free Play locations in the DFW metro area collectively as the best arcades I’ve visited in the United States. In fact, I think the fact they routinely acquire new games and swap out machines on the floor gives them an advantage over the few remaining retro Japanese arcades.

In short, THIS is how you do an arcade right. I hate the term “barcade” but I suppose this is one in the sense they have an impressive bar and kitchen on site. That said, unlike almost every other self-styled barcade I’ve visited, the drinks and food complement the games rather than serve as the primary attraction.

What sets Free Play apart is the diversity and rarity of its games. These feature some true gems on original hardware that go well beyond the dime-a-dozen Pac-Man and Centipede cabs found elsewhere. For example, the Richardson location (at the time of this writing) has an ultra-rare Planet Harriers, an Atomiswave running Dolphin Blue, the first Beast Busters, Do Don Pachi, Power Stone 2, and the original Marvel Vs. Capcom…to name just a few. I’m not really into pinball but there are quite a few of those machines on the floor too.

Whether you’re a serious arcade enthusiast or just a casual player who wants an afternoon with your kids, I can’t recommend Free Play enough.

name: Chuck Cage
text:
Think of Free Play as the best, most well-maintained arcade you ever went to as a kid, but with beer, a flat-fee entry, and all the machines set to free play. Unlike so many retro arcades, you won't find emulators and broken games. All the games are original, lovingly taken care of, and remarkably well curated. Besides all the old standards, you'll find games here you might never have seen the first time around.

The staff is knowledgeable, too. Ask them what games are new or what to check out.

name: Tokyo Tim
text: This is a fantastic, must visit place for locals and tourists and everyone else! The cost was around $14 for an adult and was the best money ever spent at a museum. And the ticket is good all day, even if you leave and revisit later the same day. Parking is $1 an hour and you will spend just under 2 hours. You will start with a guided tour and learn how the boat was lost, found, and retrieved. To aid in this, a short, 15 minute video will be watched. After which, you will see a ton of the items recovered from the boat, most on display behind glass. It is extremely impressive to see the quantity and variety of items, all displayed perfectly. We were simply overjoyed by this find and glad we took the time to visit on our drive through Kansas City.
title: Arabia Steamboat Museum

name: Tracey A
text: We booked around noon and arrived around 9pm. Our room, 130, was at the end of the hall, by an A/C unit set at 60 degrees. Upon entering, we were immediately hit with a strong mold smell. Our room A/C unit was also set at 60. We turned it to heat and began suffocating from an enveloping odor of mold/mildew. Everything--carpet and sheets, felt damp. We asked to move but were told all rooms were taken. Suspecting water damage, I found peeling wallpaper near the floor and doors in the hallway. Inspecting the room, ceiling paint was cracking, falling away, and stained with water rings. The walls are weak and give under pressure near the floor under the window. Metal fixings (hinges, pipes, hangers...) are rusted. There are cobwebs in the corners, and plenty of pubic hairs on the bathroom floor. The door sign with the room prices is yellowed, smudged (mildew?), and has hair hanging from it. The free wifi had 1 bar at best and really never stayed connected throughout our stay. This was much worse than but much more expensive than the motel we stayed at the night before.

name: Eric Bonar
text:
The staff is friendly. It's easily accessible and easy to get to downtown, only took ~20 minutes.
The outside and interior is in good condition.

My non-smoking room was on the third floor, was in good condition and didn't smell. However, the elevator and the entire 3rd floor smelled like cigarette smoke. The closet was tiny, but there were plenty of drawers in the dresser.

The room had plenty of room to walk around in and for a couple of people to sit comfortably. I had a king size bed and it was very comfortable.

Breakfast was alright. I had sausage patties, scrambled eggs, biscuits and gravy and a waffle with coffee and oj. Coffee tasted like flavored water. They also had apple juice, toast, bagels, cereal and oatmeal.

All together, I enjoyed my stay. If I'm ever back in the area, I will consider staying here again.

name: Stephanie Ahlmann
text: Do not book!  This hotel is very unclean and not maintained.  When my husband and I stayed, we found brown spots on the unwashed sheets and pillowcases, stained flooring, dirty walls, broken door and window locks, many patched holes in the wall, and a broken phone and picture frame.  We have stayed in hotels in third world countries that were cleaner and more kept up.  It took 45 minutes for them to switch us to a new room, where we discovered a crust spot on the bed cover.  Instead of an apology, the owner stated "Well, I asked the housekeeper to check it for me."  They brought a new bed cover after another 20 minutes.  We did not feel comfortable there not knowing if they even changed the sheets.  Instead of relaxing, we had to leave shortly after for our concert.  After we complained in the morning, the front desk lady asked us "What kind of crust spot was it?" in lieu of an apology.  I asked her how we were to know and why it mattered.  She then offered $10 off, which was not worthy of accepting.  The owner did not offer anything else and obviously does not take pride in her business.  There are many other hotels - you'll be happy if you book elsewhere!!

The staff has been very nice, that's my only positive thing to say. I never gripe about things but I would feel guilty not leaving the truth in a review especially for those with small children.

name: Crystal Grobe
text:
It all started when Google tried to send me through a roundabout during rush hour traffic in an unfamiliar city. Evidently, Google is not aware of any paths to this hotel that do not utilize the roundabout. That alone is enough to make me wish I booked elsewhere.

Then I arrived. The parking lot smells like a dead animal and the whole place smells like various kinds of smoke. Good luck finding an employee of you need one. And when you do find one, they'll probably give you helpful advice like cutting you off after the word 'Where' to tell you your room number is on your key packet. (Which, incidentally, was given to me separately from my key). Cool! Where's the elevator?

I've taken pictures of the broken furniture in the room, but taking pictures of the lack of cleaning would be an all night job. This place is gross. Even for a Days Inn.

name: Ben P
text:
Pros: some fun stuff for kids! Go karts, bumper boats, rock climb, trampoline jump. There are also laser tag and mini golf available. There is a game room with some arcade style games, snacks, etc. Kids will love everything here, and you might too.

Cons: EXPENSIVE! Understand before you go that tickets for just outside activities are $30 per person... For 2 hours. That's $120 for a family of 4. Want to play a doubt of mini golf? That's not included... That's another $18... Per person. So now you're up to $200. Wanna try laser tag?it's very fun, but also not included.

Your kids will want to play the arcade games to win tickets, you can buy game passes for a time limit.

During fully open operation and during the summer it is *crowded* so lines are long so be prepared to wait.

Bottom line - kids will have a blast, go on off-peak days if you can, look online or ask about packages for activities and games, and be prepared to shell out a lot of money for the afternoon; if you're not ready to either drop a couple hundred bucks or disappoint the kids by telling them "no" then maybe come back a different time.

name: James
text: Excellent service throughout my stay!  The beach room view was well worth it, large balcony angled towards the beach.  One thing worth noting is I’d consider staying on the left side facing the beach or in the inner right to avoid the partial view a restaurants roof, had the room to the right of the presidential suite for reference.  Nothing huge but worth mentioning.  The private beach is directly behind the hotel and easy to get back and forth. Multiple places to eat and all were on par with the resort.  Several other upscale amenities, activities and services are available consistent with other Hilton resorts. Another bonus is they provide shuttle service to Baytown Wharf which is close to the resort, among other places.  If you’re looking for a place to stay that is not as crowded as other beaches around with more than enough places available to dine at without going into Destin I’d strongly recommend this place on your short list.  Plan on visiting again.

name: Jonathan Brito
text:
I wish I loved this meal, but honestly I could have had better in Boston and that's not saying much.

The baked potato was delicious and very flavorful, but the strip steak with blue cheese crust was all panko breadcrumbs and very little blue cheese. The steak was also a bit tough for the $39 price tab.

Service was also very slow. 40 minute wait for a table that never came so I sat at the bar instead and then waited another 10 minutes to have my drink request taken.

The glass of red wine I chose was out of stock, so I had to choose something different and waited another 10 minutes for someone to ask if I wanted a drink. Surprisingly, the meal came out quickly, in about 15 minutes, but having to wait nearly 1.5 hours for an okay steak and a delicious baked potato was disappointing.

The restaurant was busy, but the two bartenders (and one additional bartender / waitress that kept floating in and out of the bar) with a devoted barback should be able to handle a dinner crowd.

name: Roberto Sabas
text:
It was my first time staying at a hostel and I'm glad it was at this location, close to the lake in a nice area. Compared to many a 1-star motel or hotel, it's bare bones in room amenities, but the sense of community and the savings are good reasons to consider staying in one. What comes to mind is a boarding house, which I suppose hostels are akin to, but the staff at this place are helpful and responsive to guest needs and concerns. We enjoyed the complimentary breakfast and the nice patio area. Our fellow guests were from various places and the ones we met were friendly.

Nearby are many nice restaurants, cafes, businesses, conveniences, and bars. To the east is the North Pond, and further the lake shore. You can walk, run, or bike to your heart's content (convenient for pet owners too as it's very pet friendly in the area). It's less than 15 minutes away from the conservatory and the zoo (both free). There are are wonderful museums both in the area and a little further away (but in stone's throw).

Tips: 1) bring your own food to store in the plentiful refrigerated cases (they provide bins and labels) to save on dining expenses or if you have specific dietary requirements. 2) Their parking spaces are limited so arrive within 5 minutes of check-in. It's $28 a night to park there. 3) Alternatively, use an app like SpotHero to book affordable longer term spaces in the area (12 hours to a several days). 4) the kitchen is huge and well maintained, but do your part to help keep it that way (same goes for the bathrooms). 5) if you're looking for fun things to do, check out the activities chalkboard in the lobby. 6) Be respectful, kind, and friendly to everyone there. You will get out of the experience what you put into it.

name: Ash C
text:
1 star for a subpar/gross experience at Chicago Getaway Hostel. I rented a private room for 3 nights looking for a clean/decent place to sleep and shower while I was in the city for a work project. Chicago Getaway Hostel did not fit the bill.

The Hostel is in a beautiful Lincoln Park neighborhood with tons of giant trees and you really can't find a better location to get the LP vibe but then walk a block to hop on trains/buses. The cost for a private room is comparable to a hotel room, but I chose this place because it's location was within walking distance to where I was going to be working. After looking at reviews and photos of the hostel, it seemed like a very modern and clean place that I would be comfortable staying at... unfortunately the photos were deceiving and the reviews did not represent my experience.

When I walked up to the building, I had to walk through a crowd of people gathering on the sidewalk outside the hostel smoking (great for my asthma) to enter the building. This happened every time I entered/exited the building over the next few days, which was a real turn off to me. The check in process was quick - the person checking me in rushed through all of the instructions and gave me no written document that verified what he went over, so that was fun.

My room looked nice at first glance - 2 bunk beds, a desk, shower/toilet/sink. All the essentials. Upon further investigation here's what I found (some photos attached)... the bathroom was absolutely disgusting. I don't know when it was last cleaned, but it had to have been a long time. The amount of dirt/grime built up in that shower made me feel dirtier than I was when I walked in. One shouldn't have to buy flip flops to shower in a private room bathroom they rented. There was buildup ON THE SHOWER HEAD where the clean water is supposed to come out of but there was nastiness caked on so it passed through that first.

The beds were pretty uncomfortable. The mattress was very thin and I could feel the bars through it, so it was rough sleeping. A majority of the linens had a ton of stains/loose hairs on them (especially the pillows) and they were very rough in texture. All of this combined made me feel very gross and like the room hadn't been cleaned at all. For the price of a hotel room I'd expect a much higher level of cleanliness from this place.

Needless to say, I will not be back.

Minutes after we walked into our room, I started having severe dust allergies, and the place was filthy. I was shocked because we expect so much more from a Marriott. We left for 3 hours and turned the AC down while gone.  Came back and the room was so hot we almost threw up packing up our stuff.

They did give us free breakfast for the inconvenience but would of been nice if they could of met us on the floor instead of 2 trips down to get the room and 1 trip with the luggage cart up.

They also didn't explain any charges so I had a mini panic attacks that they charged me an extra 100 for my room only to go down and have the free explained
Overall a little bit mismanaged. But the greeter is super nice and the breakfast servers have great service.

name: Myra Johnson
text:
The only reason they get 2 stars is because the towels were decent. When we got in the room we noticed there was a cabinet for a refrigerator, but no refrigerator. I called the desk and was asked if I requested one. I told her no, that I didn't think I had to since EVERY hotel I've stayed in for the last 25 or more years had one in the room. I take prescription medication that must be refrigerated. I explained that to her. She said she would notify housekeeping. Several hours later I went to the desk and asked again, stressing my need for a refrigerator, again explaining my situation. We stayed for 2 nights and never got a refrigerator. I guess i should be grateful there was an ice bucket. Hopefully it didn't compromise the effectiveness of my prescription.
In addition, there was no microwave.
When we returned to our room the housekeeper was at the end of the hall.
There was a pile of dirty towels outside our room. We went out and when we returned hours later the housekeeper was gone but the pile of towels were still there. My husband called the desk to tell them they forgot to pick them up, they thanked him and assured him it will be taken care of. They were still there this morning when we left.
I think we will stick with the Choice Hotel chain from now on.
Thank you.

name: Savannah Johnson
text: I took a gamble and commuted over an hour to visit here with my son and his buddy today after researching and finding Ray's Splash Planet online. This facility far exceeded my expectations. The dressing rooms and facility itself was clean and updated. It was $35 for all three of us (out of city residents) to swim/play all day which isn't even one ticket at other water parks. We have been to our fair share of water parks, splash pads, etc. and I have never experienced lifeguards and staff remain so continuously attentive and alert in their positions. Not once did I see a lifeguard distracted by their cell phones, talking to each other, nothing of the sort. I noticed the staff rotated positions frequently, took safety checks in their zones, and were quick to act in situations to prevent accidents or injury. As a parent, I value and appreciate these proactive practices so much. I would definitely recommend this place and will return in the future.

name: angel taylor
text:
For nearly $500/night, I was expecting more than the standard hotel however, it was nothing more than average.  The front desk was nice but I had to walk by an overly full garbage can when walking in, so that set the tone. I wouldn’t mind really, but it was that way every day that I was there. The can in the pool area was also overflowing by lunch and never changed until the end of the day.
This place has a smaller than average pool with very little seating. Approx 20 lounge chairs and there was room for many more. There were no umbrellas or tables In the pool area and very little shade.  There is a small bar outside that had some shaded seating. Prices for cocktails was $12+ .  Bring your ant spray, as there was an abundance of ants around the pool.  The breakfast seating area is a decent size but it doesn’t accommodate the amount of people that can stay at that hotel. I know it’s not reasonable to plan for every patron to eat breakfast at the same time however, when it’s 15-20 min wait to make a waffle or wait on some other item to come out so you can have something before they close the doors on you, then it’s a problem.
Our room had a rusted, I mean RUSTED, like throw it away it’s so rusty, lamp.

Room was very clean, gulf view, great AC, and it was quiet. Across the street are a few restaurants, walking distance to Starbucks. Publix and Walmart very close by.

Construction is starting next door on new giant condos so the peace and quiet May be gone soon…. That’s also the same side as the bar.

name: Cassie Nix
text:
The pros were the location, the view and the walk to the beach. We paid for an oceanfront view, and the view was gorgeous. Breakfast was also great. Most of the staff we interacted with were lovely.

I don’t usually nitpick, but I was paying $400 a night and find some things just not excusable at that price.
They don’t have daily maid service, and you have to go down to get towels/toilet paper and take out your own trash. Again, for the price I was paying, I think daily service would be expected. You can only get a full service every 5 days.
They are dog friendly, which is amazing…but there was no place to take them to the bathroom. The abandoned lot next door was what we opted for, but it was filled with thorny and burred plants. They are not allowed on the beach (city law) so there are really no options. At one point we tried to use a tiny patch of grass outside the fence, but the bartender from the pool told us it was gross to have them within eyesight and we needed to take our dogs off property to use the bathroom.

name: Sandra Dow
text:
💙💜⛱️What a wonderful stay here! Employees are firendly at the front desk and the cleaning team.

Rooms are pretty plain and simple, but that doesnt matter. I cant imagine many people will spend much time in their room, except to sleep.🛌 The hotel🏢 is directly on the beach! 🏖👐🙌👏

A lounge chair rental service w is available for rent at $35 a day. You can walk directly from the hotel to the beach via a wooden  boardwalk w a few stairs. The white sand is so soft and the sound of the waves just took our stress away. ⛱️

Outside pool and hottub also face the beach.

Parking permit for the garage at check in. Easily elevator access frlm the garage too.

Most rooms with balconies facing the ocean are double beds🛌 instead of kings, which could be good for families.

🧽Very clean, did I mention clean!!!🧼 Absolutely will return to this Hampton when we are in town again. Very satisfied multi year diamond member here.

There is an outside tiki bar for drinks and the full beach affect too! 🍸🍷🍹

During the stay a 🌀storm blew in and it was very cold, so we hit the hot tub. I saw alot of kiddos playing in the pool and a few adults. It is a heated pool, but not as warm as the hot tub🏟, so the hot tub it was for me.

text: A lot to like about this beachfront hampton inn - great location, small pool and beautiful lobby. name: Kathi Davidson
text:
We stayed here for several nights. It was our first visit to the Gulf Shores/Orange Beach area. This inn was a nice little place to stay.
The hotel itself is in decent condition with updated modern designs and comfort. The doors going into the room and balcony could have used a little maintenence. The room had a spectacular view of the Gulf and we enjoy the balcony alot. The pool/hottub was clean enough and a had great temps every time. Their beach area was always kept nice and we spent alot of time just enjoying the waves.
The breakfast was always served hot and there was always plenty even though we often ate towards the end of the meal time. They serve you instead of you picking what you want - Covid19 restrictions.
The only reason they are losing a star - we had to ask for everything. Since they are not cleaning the rooms and restocking supplies and clean towels each day, we were left to ask for toilet paper, new paper cups, coffee, etc. Several times it seemed as though they didn't want to get anything for us and that we were imposing on them to ask for a trash bags or whatever. I would suggest having a time frame each morning that the guests could get what they need without "disturbing" the front desk staff. Other than that the staff was pleasant.
One of the elevators was out of service the entire time we were there. Apparently it has been out for several weeks.. while most of time it wasn't too long of a wait, during the weekends it got a little crazy.
The Tiki bartender (Oscar) is funny! Enjoy as few beers with him.

title: Courtyard by Marriott Charlotte Matthews
description:
Off the I-485, this straightforward hotel is 8.3 miles from Charlotte National Golf Club.
 Contemporary rooms offer free WiFi, desks with ergonomic chairs and flat-screen TVs with premium cable channels, plus minifridges, microwaves and coffeemakers. Suites add separate living areas.
 Social spaces include a living room-style lobby. The American restaurant serves breakfast. There's also a business center with workstations and printers, and 2 meeting rooms. Other amenities include a seasonal outdoor pool, indoor whirlpool and exercise room, plus free on-site parking.
label: real

name: Russell Lescault
text:
Getting to the hotel was confusing, specially at night; going south on Independence Blvd there is no left turn into the hotel lot, so Google maps takes you around the block behind the hotel. This would be fine except there are no signs nor lights to see the entrance.  Also my room was not ready at 7 pm and I had to wait; when I got to my room, there were no trash cans in the room. I asked for a trash can and I was given a toilet plunger, which did not really help with the trash.
Other than that, the hotel was extremely clean, comfortable and located in a nice area.

name: Leo Nid
text: When was the last time you were so happy, that tears came down your eyes? Wedding? Winning something you didn't expect? Well tasting the Mahbarawi is the first time that I cried from food being that good. I generally don't trust restaurants that only have five reviews, where all five are four or five stars, and most of them come from reviewers with little to no reviews. Well, I'm glad that I took the risk. For less than $20 I enjoyed one of the best meals of my life, with a lovely cup of tea, and service as good as one could hope for. They customized the spice level for me, and the cabbage, potatoes, beets, lentils, and greens perfectly balanced the spiciness of the meat. The flavors, the texture, the presentation, were all a symphony to the senses. If I lived in the area, I would eat here at least once a week. It's a true testament to Yelp that I found this establishment, as it's such a tiny, non-descript building, that I would have driven right by it.

name: Mikayla In (이나현)
text: Although I wasn't very familiar with Ethiopian cuisine, I had a great time at this restaurant. The food was absolutely delicious, and the price was very fair, especially considering that we ordered a platter for four people and couldn't even finish it! My friend really enjoyed the mango smoothie, but I found it a bit too sweet and heavy. The one downside was that the restaurant was very busy, and they occasionally forgot to bring our additional orders. Also, they charged us the wrong amount, so it's important to double-check your tab during checkout. However, despite these minor issues, the food was superb and definitely worth a visit for anyone in the area looking to try something new.
